Materials were synthesized through a hydrothermal carbonization technique (
                           Fig. S1
                        ). Briefly, wolfberry (3 g) was added into 5 mL of K4[Fe(CN)6]∙3H2O solution with different concentrations (0 and 0.02 mol/L) in a reaction kettle and carbonized for 8 h at 200°C to prepare Fe-free doped composites (N/BC/CQDs) and Fe/N/BC/CQDs, respectively. After cooling to room temperature, the mixture was centrifuged at 8000 rpm for 15 min to collect the lower solid layer and supernatant. The lower solid layer were dried at 60℃ for 6 h, ground, and sieved to obtain a size fraction < 150 µm (N/BC/CQDs and Fe/N/BC/CQDs). The supernatant was filtered using a 0.22 μm aqueous filter head and dialyzed in a 1000 D dialysis bag for 2 d (N/CQDs and Fe/N/CQDs). The Fe/N/BC/CQDs composite was thoroughly rinsed with copious amounts of deionized water until no fluorescent substances were detected in the effluent (confirmed by fluorescence spectrophotometry at 365 nm excitation wavelength), yielding the final Fe/N/BC material.

Free radical trapping experiments were performed to identify the main active substances in the photocatalytic reaction. Different scavengers including p-benzoquinone (PBQ), ethylenediaminetetraacetic acid disodium salt (EDTA-2Na), isopropanol (IPA), furfuryl alcohol (FFA) were added into the reaction system to capture superoxide radicals (•O2
                        –), photo-generated holes (h+
                        ), hydroxyl radicals (•OH), and singlet oxygen (1O2), respectively. The initial concentration of PBQ, EDTA-2Na, IPA, and FFA were all 100 mmol/L.

Based on IUPAC classification and N2 adsorption isotherms, Fe/N/BC/CQDs was type I isotherm, which reflected the phenomenon of micropore filling on microporous adsorbents (
                           Fig. S4
                        ). The surface of Fe/N/BC/CQDs had a high density of small pores due to the filling of CQDs, with mean pore diameter of 1.985 nm and total pore volume of 0.979 cm3/mg.

The spectral properties of carbon quantum dots (
                           Fig. S5
                        ) could be obtained from their fluorescence spectra. Under 365 nm excitation, the Fe/N/CQDs exhibited a strong emission peak at 420 nm, with a fluorescence intensity of 833.7 a.u.—significantly higher than that of N/CQDs (705.3 a.u.). This enhanced fluorescence performance suggests that Fe/N co-doping effectively improves the optoelectronic properties of CQDs, likely due to optimized electronic transitions and reduced charge recombination. The superior fluorescence efficiency of Fe/N/CQDs was expected to facilitate photoexcitation and charge carrier separation, thereby enhancing their photocatalytic activity.

The adsorption and photocatalytic degradation of sulfonamide and fluoroquinolone antibiotics by Fe/N/BC/CQDs were investigated under dark and visible light conditions. After a 60-min dark reaction, 20.00 %, 13.46 %, 11.25 %, 6.46 %, 8.79 %, 15.63 % of NOR, STZ, SMZ, SMD, SDM, and SM2 were removed due to the pore structure composition of the Fe/N/BC/CQDs materials. The adsorption equilibrium was reached in 1 h (Fig. 2

                        a, b), while the control experiment without Fe/N/BC/CQDs almost could not remove the target sulfonamide and fluoroquinolone antibiotics (
                           Fig. S6
                        ). Photocatalytic degradation was essentially completed within 3 h, and the degradation efficiency of Fe/N/BC/CQDs for sulfonamide and fluoroquinolone antibiotics followed the order of SMZ (89.23 %) > STZ (86.51 %) > NOR (84.20 %) > SDM (77.44 %) > SMD (76.88 %) > SM2 (74.21 %). Upon exposure to light, the degradation efficiency of sulfonamide and fluoroquinolone antibiotics was significantly enhanced. The degradation pathway of sulfonamide and fluoroquinolone antibiotics by Fe/N/BC/CQDs material involved a dynamic adsorption-photocatalytic degradation–adsorption process. The degradation efficiency differences between sulfonamide and fluoroquinolone antibiotics by Fe/N/BC/CQDs primarily stem from their distinct molecular architectures and electronic properties. The photocatalytic performance of Fe/N/BC/CQDs was mainly attributed to the addition of N atoms considering that N atoms modulated the electronic structure of the neighboring C atoms and thereby increased the number of positive charges and accelerated the generation of free radicals [48]. Additionally, the presence of Fe/N/CQDs enhanced the utilization of nature light, which further improved the photocatalytic efficiency. Compared with previous photocatalytic materials (
                           Table S1
                        ), Fe/N/BC/CQDs material prepared in this study did not require additional oxidizing agents. By contrast, the Fe/N/BC/CQDs material increased the use of natural light and reduced photocatalytic energy consumption, making it an ideal method for long-term photocatalytic degradation of antibiotics in the environments. Meanwhile, it could be easily synthesized in one step, making it more cost-effective and environmentally friendly. The stability of photocatalytic materials plays a crucial role in practical applications. The post-reaction Fe/N/BC/CQDs composite was recovered and subjected to comprehensive characterization by XRD (
                           Fig. S7
                        ) and SEM (
                           Fig. S8
                        ). This conclusively demonstrated that the material maintained its original crystalline structure and morphological features after photocatalytic reaction. As demonstrated by five consecutive cycling tests, the Fe/N/BC/CQDs exhibit sustained photocatalytic degradation activity for sulfonamide and fluoroquinolone antibiotics, represented by SMZ (
                           Fig. S9
                        ).

Combined with the mass spectra (
                           Fig. S16
                        ), it could be inferred that the S-N bond would be broken first to form SM2-1 (m/z 158) and SM2-2 (m/z 124) (Fig. 3
                        f and 

                           Table S7
                        ). SM2-3 (m/z 84) could be formed via the SM2-2 pyrimidine ring-opening reaction [55].

The ecotoxicological assessment was conducted through 24-hour exposure experiments using rotifers (Brachionus calyciflorus) to evaluate the acute toxicity of sulfonamide fluoroquinolone antibiotics photocatalytic degradation intermediates generated by Fe/N/BC/CQDs treatment. Comparative analysis revealed no statistically significant difference in rotifer mortality rates between the parent compounds and their degradation products after 24-hour exposure (
                           Fig. S17
                        ). Furthermore, the maintenance of rotifer viability at levels comparable to controls strongly supports the environmental safety of this Fe/N/BC/CQDs, confirming its potential for practical implementation in real-world wastewater treatment.
